So this is a little worse than I initially thought, since IIRC the pre-commit hook will remove the plugins as soon as it auto-updates the baseline.

### The Why

So in [secrets_collection.py](https://github.com/Yelp/detect-secrets/blob/e15d0a99697900273abe96ca1387446f22c439dd/detect_secrets/core/secrets_collection.py#L77-L106) we load the baseline in, but don't take `plugins` into account. We need to turn these into a proper tuple, the way [`initialize_plugins`](https://github.com/Yelp/detect-secrets/blob/e15d0a99697900273abe96ca1387446f22c439dd/detect_secrets/plugins/__init__.py#L96) turns `args.plugins` into a proper tuple.

However, we cannot just call `initialize_plugins` as that expects e.g.

```python
        assert args.plugins == {
            'HexHighEntropyString': {
                'hex_limit': [3],
            },
            'Base64HighEntropyString': {
                'base64_limit': [4.5],
            },
            'PrivateKeyDetector': {},
        }
```

Not a list we have in `_load_baseline_from_dict`:

```python
[
    {
        'limit': 4.5,
        'name': 'Base64HighEntropyString'
    },
    {
        'limit': 3,
        'name': 'HexHighEntropyString'
    },
    {
        'name': 'PrivateKeyDetector'
    }
]
```


### The Solution

So I tried to see if calling [`_initialize_plugin`](https://github.com/Yelp/detect-secrets/blob/e15d0a99697900273abe96ca1387446f22c439dd/detect_secrets/plugins/__init__.py#L123-L138) direct, would help, but since it takes `*args` instead of `**kwargs`, I could have hard-coded passing in `limit` from the dict, but that's bad and hard-coded.

Then I wondered how [`_initialize_plugin`](https://github.com/Yelp/detect-secrets/blob/e15d0a99697900273abe96ca1387446f22c439dd/detect_secrets/plugins/__init__.py#L123-L138) is called in the first place, from [`initialize_plugins`](https://github.com/Yelp/detect-secrets/blob/e15d0a99697900273abe96ca1387446f22c439dd/detect_secrets/plugins/__init__.py#L96):

```python
        args = []
        if init_values:
            key = list(init_values.keys())[0]
            args.append(init_values[key][0])

        output.append(_initialize_plugin(plugin_name, *args))
```

This is bad b/c we're depending on the order of a `.keys()` to pass in `*args`, I think we should only be using `**kwargs`.

After it is fixed to use `**kwargs`, I can call `[`_initialize_plugin`](https://github.com/Yelp/detect-secrets/blob/e15d0a99697900273abe96ca1387446f22c439dd/detect_secrets/plugins/__init__.py#L123-L138)` directly. (From a wrapper function in `plugins/__init__.py` of course, not from `secrets_collection.py`. Though we might want to make a different file in `plugins/`, as putting a lot of code in `__init__.py`'s is generally frowned upon.)

